article.description:
Sophia Young's two free throws with 42 seconds
left put San Antonio ahead for good, and the Silver Stars rallied from a 14-point deficit for a 89-87 win over the Seattle Storm on Sunday night.
article.headline: Silver Stars erase 14-point deficit to beat Storm
article.linkText: Silver Stars storm Seattle, win fourth straight on road
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- In their previous two games, the San Antonio
Silver Stars showed they can build a big lead and hold off a late
charge. On Sunday night, they showed some resiliency and their own
ability to rally from behind.

Sophia Young's two free throws with 42 seconds left put San
Antonio ahead for good, and the Silver Stars rallied from a
14-point deficit for a 89-87 win over the Seattle Storm.

San Antonio improved to 4-0 on the road for the first time in
franchise history -- including victories in Houston, Sacramento and
Seattle. The previous best start came in 2001, when the team was in
Utah and won its first three road contests before losing to
Washington.

"I was just pleased we didn't fold our tents when they hit us
hard early," San Antonio coach Dan Hughes said. "We kept coming
back, kept coming back and we got good play throughout our
lineup."

Young finished with 14 points and 11 rebounds, the rookie's
third double-double in six games. Kendra Wecker and LaToya Thomas
each scored 15 points to lead the Silver Stars, who scored the
final five points and held Seattle scoreless over the last 1:50.

Six San Antonio players finished in double figures, and the
Silver Stars outrebounded Seattle 37-21, including 18 offensive
rebounds.

At the end of the third quarter, San Antonio had 13 offensive
rebounds and Seattle 13 rebounds total. The Silver Stars also had
21 second-chance points.

"Our scouting report was to keep them off the board as much as
possible. That was the focus," Young said. "The stats really show
a lot, but we didn't think we outrebounded them this much."

Young's biggest rebound may have come in the final moments. The
6-foot-1 rookie corralled Dalma Ivanyi's airball with 8 seconds
left and was fouled. She made one of two free throws to make it
89-87, and Seattle's Betty Lennox missed a 14-foot jumper in the
final seconds.

Lauren Jackson scored 21 points for Seattle, which has not won
consecutive games this season. Sue Bird added 18 points and Iziane
Castro Marquez scored 14.

"We did a great job defensively, we shot the ball well, took
care of the ball, got to the free-throw line. We just didn't close
out the deal with the offensive glass," Seattle coach Anne Donovan
said.

San Antonio scored just four points during a 5½-minute span of
the fourth quarter, but scored seven straight to pull even at 84
with 2:06 left on Thomas' jumper.

Jackson then converted a three-point play for Seattle with 1:50
left -- the final points for the Storm.

Agnieszka Bibrzycka scored 12 points for San Antonio and Vicki
Johnson added 11.

"That's the best thing about this team, no body cares who
scores," Johnson said.

Trailing 51-39 early in the third quarter, San Antonio went on a
14-2 run keyed by 11 points from Wecker, including three
3-pointers, to pull even at 53. San Antonio trailed by 14 in the
first half, as Seattle made nine of its first 10 shots and shot 58
percent in the first half.

The Silver Stars eventually took their first lead at 65-63 late
in the third on Young's basket. The lead grew to six early in the
fourth quarter, but Jackson made a pair of 3-pointers to pull
Seattle even at 73-all with 8 minutes left.

The Storm played without forward Wendy Palmer, out with an
injured left Achilles'. Palmer was wearing a protective boot on her
foot and was expected to have further examination on Monday. Palmer
is averaging 9.4 points and 7.6 rebounds.
